The paper deals with the construction and properties of Delaunay graphs, which are a fundamental concept in computational geometry. The use of line segments to constrain the edges of the graph is a common technique in computational geometry, and is often used to model real-world scenarios. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the spanning ratio of the graph, which is a measure of its efficiency as a network. This suggests that it could also be classified under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) or cs.GR (Graph Theory). The paper also introduces a new construction method for the graph, which could be of interest to researchers in cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) or cs.CC (Computational Complexity).
